-- Japan, Singapore, Korea, Malaysia, Thailand: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2010-10-03T22:56:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-03/japan-singapore-korea-malaysia-thailand-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: The Bank of Japan is set to start a two-day policy
meeting today. The central bank is forecast to keep the
benchmark interest at 0.1 percent, according to the median
estimate of economists in a Bloomberg News survey. Japan’s Chief
Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold media briefings at
11 a.m. and 4 p.m.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 rose 2.5 basis points to 0.955 percent on Oct. 1, according
to Japan Bond Trading Co., the nation’s largest interdealer debt
broker. A basis point is 0.01 percentage point.  The yen traded at 83.37 per dollar at 7:53 a.m. in Tokyo.  Malaysia: The central bank will sell 1 billion ringgit
($324 million) of 65-day Islamic notes. It will also sell a
total of 4 billion ringgit in 91- and 182-day conventional notes.  The yield on the 3.835 percent bond due August 2015 was
3.23 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0800.  Singapore: The government will sell S$3.7 billion ($2.8
billion) of 91-day Treasury bills.  The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due September 2020 was
2.04 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3130.  South Korea: The government will report foreign-exchange
reserves data for September. Reserves fell to $285.4 billion
from a record $286.0 billion in August.  The central bank will sell 400 billion won ($355 million)
of 182-day notes and 600 billion won of three-year bonds today.
It also plans to sell 500 billion won of 28-day notes and 1
trillion won of 91 day debt.  The yield on the 3.75 percent debt due June 2013 was 3.27
percent, according to Korea Stock Exchange. The won traded at
1,130.45.  Thailand: The government will sell a combined 3 billion
baht ($99 million) of 28-, 91- and 182-day bills.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note maturing March 2021 was
3.11 percent. The baht was at 30.21.  To contact the reporter on this story:
